slides.title: Contention Against the French Intelligence Bill
slides.text:
In France, advocacy against Internet surveillance has been historically underdeveloped compared to countries such as the US, the UK or Germany. But after a failed mobilization an overhaul of the legal regime underlying administrative access to metadata in late 2013 (Military Planning Act), several civil society groups decided to broker new connections by creating the "Oberservatoire des Libertés Numériques" (OLN) in January 2014.

By the time the Intelligence Bill was introduced in Parliament, in March 2015, post-Snowden contention had finally developed in France. During the three-month long parliamentary debate on the Bill (April-June 2015), advocacy groups and lawyers organizations were able to lead the opposition to the Bill, while benefiting from the support of variety of other groups and actors typical of post-Snowden mobilizations against secret state surveillance.
